6991           previous = NULL;
6992           continue;
6993           }
6994         bravalue = OP_ASSERT_NOT;
6995         cd->assert_depth += 1;
6996         break;
6997 
6998 
6999         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7000         case CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN:              /* Lookbehind or named define */
7001         switch (ptr[1])
7002           {
7003           case CHAR_EQUALS_SIGN:               /* Positive lookbehind */
7004           bravalue = OP_ASSERTBACK;
7005           cd->assert_depth += 1;
7006           ptr += 2;
7007           break;
7008 
7009           case CHAR_EXCLAMATION_MARK:          /* Negative lookbehind */
7010           bravalue = OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT;
7011           cd->assert_depth += 1;
7012           ptr += 2;
7013           break;
7014 
7015           default:                /* Could be name define, else bad */
7016           if (MAX_255(ptr[1]) && (cd->ctypes[ptr[1]] & ctype_word) != 0)
7017             goto DEFINE_NAME;
7018           ptr++;                  /* Correct offset for error */
7019           *errorcodeptr = ERR24;
7020           goto FAILED;
7021           }
7022         break;
7023 
7024 
7025         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7026         case CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN:           /* One-time brackets */
7027         bravalue = OP_ONCE;
7028         ptr++;
7029         break;
7030 
7031 
7032         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7033         case CHAR_C:                 /* Callout - may be followed by digits; */
7034         previous_callout = code;     /* Save for later completion */
7035         after_manual_callout = 1;    /* Skip one item before completing */
7036         *code++ = OP_CALLOUT;
7037           {
7038           int n = 0;
7039           ptr++;
7040           while(IS_DIGIT(*ptr))
7041             n = n * 10 + *ptr++ - CHAR_0;
7042           if (*ptr != CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS)
7043             {
7044             *errorcodeptr = ERR39;
7045             goto FAILED;
7046             }
7047           if (n > 255)
7048             {
7049             *errorcodeptr = ERR38;
7050             goto FAILED;
7051             }
7052           *code++ = n;
7053           PUT(code, 0, (int)(ptr - cd->start_pattern + 1)); /* Pattern offset */
7054           PUT(code, LINK_SIZE, 0);                          /* Default length */
7055           code += 2 * LINK_SIZE;
7056           }
7057         previous = NULL;
7058         continue;
7059 
7060 
7061         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7062         case CHAR_P:              /* Python-style named subpattern handling */
7063         if (*(++ptr) == CHAR_EQUALS_SIGN ||
7064             *ptr == CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN)  /* Reference or recursion */
7065           {
7066           is_recurse = *ptr == CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN;
7067           terminator = CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS;
7068           goto NAMED_REF_OR_RECURSE;
7069           }
7070         else if (*ptr != CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN)  /* Test for Python-style defn */
7071           {
7072           *errorcodeptr = ERR41;
7073           goto FAILED;
7074           }
7075         /* Fall through to handle (?P< as (?< is handled */
7076 
7077 
7078         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7079         DEFINE_NAME:    /* Come here from (?< handling */
7080         case CHAR_APOSTROPHE:
7081         terminator = (*ptr == CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN)?
7082           CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN : CHAR_APOSTROPHE;
7083         name = ++ptr;
7084         if (IS_DIGIT(*ptr))
7085           {
7086           *errorcodeptr = ERR84;   /* Group name must start with non-digit */
7087           goto FAILED;
7088           }
7089         while (MAX_255(*ptr) && (cd->ctypes[*ptr] & ctype_word) != 0) ptr++;
7090         namelen = (int)(ptr - name);
7091 
7092         /* In the pre-compile phase, do a syntax check, remember the longest
7093         name, and then remember the group in a vector, expanding it if
7094         necessary. Duplicates for the same number are skipped; other duplicates
7095         are checked for validity. In the actual compile, there is nothing to
7096         do. */
7097 
7098         if (lengthptr != NULL)
7099           {
7100           named_group *ng;
7101           pcre_uint32 number = cd->bracount + 1;
7102 
7103           if (*ptr != (pcre_uchar)terminator)
7104             {
7105             *errorcodeptr = ERR42;
7106             goto FAILED;
7107             }
7108 
7109           if (cd->names_found >= MAX_NAME_COUNT)
7110             {
7111             *errorcodeptr = ERR49;
7112             goto FAILED;
7113             }
7114 
7115           if (namelen + IMM2_SIZE + 1 > cd->name_entry_size)
7116             {
7117             cd->name_entry_size = namelen + IMM2_SIZE + 1;
7118             if (namelen > MAX_NAME_SIZE)
7119               {
7120               *errorcodeptr = ERR48;
7121               goto FAILED;
7122               }
7123             }
7124 
7125           /* Scan the list to check for duplicates. For duplicate names, if the
7126           number is the same, break the loop, which causes the name to be
7127           discarded; otherwise, if DUPNAMES is not set, give an error.
7128           If it is set, allow the name with a different number, but continue
7129           scanning in case this is a duplicate with the same number. For
7130           non-duplicate names, give an error if the number is duplicated. */
7131 
7132           ng = cd->named_groups;
7133           for (i = 0; i < cd->names_found; i++, ng++)
7134             {
7135             if (namelen == ng->length &&
7136                 STRNCMP_UC_UC(name, ng->name, namelen) == 0)
7137               {
7138               if (ng->number == number) break;
7139               if ((options & PCRE_DUPNAMES) == 0)
7140                 {
7141                 *errorcodeptr = ERR43;
7142                 goto FAILED;
7143                 }
7144               cd->dupnames = TRUE;  /* Duplicate names exist */
7145               }
7146             else if (ng->number == number)
7147               {
7148               *errorcodeptr = ERR65;
7149               goto FAILED;
7150               }
7151             }
7152 
7153           if (i >= cd->names_found)     /* Not a duplicate with same number */
7154             {
7155             /* Increase the list size if necessary */
7156 
7157             if (cd->names_found >= cd->named_group_list_size)
7158               {
7159               int newsize = cd->named_group_list_size * 2;
7160               named_group *newspace = (PUBL(malloc))
7161                 (newsize * sizeof(named_group));
7162 
7163               if (newspace == NULL)
7164                 {
7165                 *errorcodeptr = ERR21;
7166                 goto FAILED;
7167                 }
7168 
7169               memcpy(newspace, cd->named_groups,
7170                 cd->named_group_list_size * sizeof(named_group));
7171               if (cd->named_group_list_size > NAMED_GROUP_LIST_SIZE)
7172                 (PUBL(free))((void *)cd->named_groups);
7173               cd->named_groups = newspace;
7174               cd->named_group_list_size = newsize;
7175               }
7176 
7177             cd->named_groups[cd->names_found].name = name;
7178             cd->named_groups[cd->names_found].length = namelen;
7179             cd->named_groups[cd->names_found].number = number;
7180             cd->names_found++;
7181             }
7182           }
7183 
7184         ptr++;                    /* Move past > or ' in both passes. */
7185         goto NUMBERED_GROUP;
7186 
7187 
7188         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7189         case CHAR_AMPERSAND:            /* Perl recursion/subroutine syntax */
7190         terminator = CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS;
7191         is_recurse = TRUE;
7192         /* Fall through */
7193 
7194         /* We come here from the Python syntax above that handles both
7195         references (?P=name) and recursion (?P>name), as well as falling
7196         through from the Perl recursion syntax (?&name). We also come here from
7197         the Perl \k<name> or \k'name' back reference syntax and the \k{name}
7198         .NET syntax, and the Oniguruma \g<...> and \g'...' subroutine syntax. */
7199 
7200         NAMED_REF_OR_RECURSE:
7201         name = ++ptr;
7202         if (IS_DIGIT(*ptr))
7203           {
7204           *errorcodeptr = ERR84;   /* Group name must start with non-digit */
7205           goto FAILED;
7206           }
7207         while (MAX_255(*ptr) && (cd->ctypes[*ptr] & ctype_word) != 0) ptr++;
7208         namelen = (int)(ptr - name);
7209 
7210         /* In the pre-compile phase, do a syntax check. We used to just set
7211         a dummy reference number, because it was not used in the first pass.
7212         However, with the change of recursive back references to be atomic,
7213         we have to look for the number so that this state can be identified, as
7214         otherwise the incorrect length is computed. If it's not a backwards
7215         reference, the dummy number will do. */
7216 
7217         if (lengthptr != NULL)
7218           {
7219           named_group *ng;
7220           recno = 0;
7221 
7222           if (namelen == 0)
7223             {
7224             *errorcodeptr = ERR62;
7225             goto FAILED;
7226             }
7227           if (*ptr != (pcre_uchar)terminator)
7228             {
7229             *errorcodeptr = ERR42;
7230             goto FAILED;
7231             }
7232           if (namelen > MAX_NAME_SIZE)
7233             {
7234             *errorcodeptr = ERR48;
7235             goto FAILED;
7236             }
7237 
7238           /* Count named back references. */
7239 
7240           if (!is_recurse) cd->namedrefcount++;
7241 
7242           /* We have to allow for a named reference to a duplicated name (this
7243           cannot be determined until the second pass). This needs an extra
7244           16-bit data item. */
7245 
7246           *lengthptr += IMM2_SIZE;
7247 
7248           /* If this is a forward reference and we are within a (?|...) group,
7249           the reference may end up as the number of a group which we are
7250           currently inside, that is, it could be a recursive reference. In the
7251           real compile this will be picked up and the reference wrapped with
7252           OP_ONCE to make it atomic, so we must space in case this occurs. */
7253 
7254           /* In fact, this can happen for a non-forward reference because
7255           another group with the same number might be created later. This
7256           issue is fixed "properly" in PCRE2. As PCRE1 is now in maintenance
7257           only mode, we finesse the bug by allowing more memory always. */
7258 
7259           *lengthptr += 2 + 2*LINK_SIZE;
7260 
7261           /* It is even worse than that. The current reference may be to an
7262           existing named group with a different number (so apparently not
7263           recursive) but which later on is also attached to a group with the
7264           current number. This can only happen if $(| has been previous
7265           encountered. In that case, we allow yet more memory, just in case.
7266           (Again, this is fixed "properly" in PCRE2. */
7267 
7268           if (cd->dupgroups) *lengthptr += 4 + 4*LINK_SIZE;
7269 
7270           /* Otherwise, check for recursion here. The name table does not exist
7271           in the first pass; instead we must scan the list of names encountered
7272           so far in order to get the number. If the name is not found, leave
7273           the value of recno as 0 for a forward reference. */
7274 
7275           else
7276             {
7277             ng = cd->named_groups;
7278             for (i = 0; i < cd->names_found; i++, ng++)
7279               {
7280               if (namelen == ng->length &&
7281                   STRNCMP_UC_UC(name, ng->name, namelen) == 0)
7282                 {
7283                 open_capitem *oc;
7284                 recno = ng->number;
7285                 if (is_recurse) break;
7286                 for (oc = cd->open_caps; oc != NULL; oc = oc->next)
7287                   {
7288                   if (oc->number == recno)
7289                     {
7290                     oc->flag = TRUE;
7291                     break;
7292                     }
7293                   }
7294                 }
7295               }
7296             }
7297           }
7298 
7299         /* In the real compile, search the name table. We check the name
7300         first, and then check that we have reached the end of the name in the
7301         table. That way, if the name is longer than any in the table, the
7302         comparison will fail without reading beyond the table entry. */
7303 
7304         else
7305           {
7306           slot = cd->name_table;
7307           for (i = 0; i < cd->names_found; i++)
7308             {
7309             if (STRNCMP_UC_UC(name, slot+IMM2_SIZE, namelen) == 0 &&
7310                 slot[IMM2_SIZE+namelen] == 0)
7311               break;
7312             slot += cd->name_entry_size;
7313             }
7314 
7315           if (i < cd->names_found)
7316             {
7317             recno = GET2(slot, 0);
7318             }
7319           else
7320             {
7321             *errorcodeptr = ERR15;
7322             goto FAILED;
7323             }
7324           }
7325 
7326         /* In both phases, for recursions, we can now go to the code than
7327         handles numerical recursion. */
7328 
7329         if (is_recurse) goto HANDLE_RECURSION;
7330 
7331         /* In the second pass we must see if the name is duplicated. If so, we
7332         generate a different opcode. */
7333 
7334         if (lengthptr == NULL && cd->dupnames)
7335           {
7336           int count = 1;
7337           unsigned int index = i;
7338           pcre_uchar *cslot = slot + cd->name_entry_size;
7339 
7340           for (i++; i < cd->names_found; i++)
7341             {
7342             if (STRCMP_UC_UC(slot + IMM2_SIZE, cslot + IMM2_SIZE) != 0) break;
7343             count++;
7344             cslot += cd->name_entry_size;
7345             }
7346 
7347           if (count > 1)
7348             {
7349             if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET) firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7350             previous = code;
7351             item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
7352             *code++ = ((options & PCRE_CASELESS) != 0)? OP_DNREFI : OP_DNREF;
7353             PUT2INC(code, 0, index);
7354             PUT2INC(code, 0, count);
7355 
7356             /* Process each potentially referenced group. */
7357 
7358             for (; slot < cslot; slot += cd->name_entry_size)
7359               {
7360               open_capitem *oc;
7361               recno = GET2(slot, 0);
7362               cd->backref_map |= (recno < 32)? (1 << recno) : 1;
7363               if (recno > cd->top_backref) cd->top_backref = recno;
7364 
7365               /* Check to see if this back reference is recursive, that it, it
7366               is inside the group that it references. A flag is set so that the
7367               group can be made atomic. */
7368 
7369               for (oc = cd->open_caps; oc != NULL; oc = oc->next)
7370                 {
7371                 if (oc->number == recno)
7372                   {
7373                   oc->flag = TRUE;
7374                   break;
7375                   }
7376                 }
7377               }
7378 
7379             continue;  /* End of back ref handling */
7380             }
7381           }
7382 
7383         /* First pass, or a non-duplicated name. */
7384 
7385         goto HANDLE_REFERENCE;
7386 
7387 
7388         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7389         case CHAR_R:              /* Recursion, same as (?0) */
7390         recno = 0;
7391         if (*(++ptr) != CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS)
7392           {
7393           *errorcodeptr = ERR29;
7394           goto FAILED;
7395           }
7396         goto HANDLE_RECURSION;
7397 
7398 
7399         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7400         case CHAR_MINUS: case CHAR_PLUS:  /* Recursion or subroutine */
7401         case CHAR_0: case CHAR_1: case CHAR_2: case CHAR_3: case CHAR_4:
7402         case CHAR_5: case CHAR_6: case CHAR_7: case CHAR_8: case CHAR_9:
7403           {
7404           const pcre_uchar *called;
7405           terminator = CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS;
7406 
7407           /* Come here from the \g<...> and \g'...' code (Oniguruma
7408           compatibility). However, the syntax has been checked to ensure that
7409           the ... are a (signed) number, so that neither ERR63 nor ERR29 will
7410           be called on this path, nor with the jump to OTHER_CHAR_AFTER_QUERY
7411           ever be taken. */
7412 
7413           HANDLE_NUMERICAL_RECURSION:
7414 
7415           if ((refsign = *ptr) == CHAR_PLUS)
7416             {
7417             ptr++;
7418             if (!IS_DIGIT(*ptr))
7419               {
7420               *errorcodeptr = ERR63;
7421               goto FAILED;
7422               }
7423             }
7424           else if (refsign == CHAR_MINUS)
7425             {
7426             if (!IS_DIGIT(ptr[1]))
7427               goto OTHER_CHAR_AFTER_QUERY;
7428             ptr++;
7429             }
7430 
7431           recno = 0;
7432           while(IS_DIGIT(*ptr))
7433             {
7434             if (recno > INT_MAX / 10 - 1) /* Integer overflow */
7435               {
7436               while (IS_DIGIT(*ptr)) ptr++;
7437               *errorcodeptr = ERR61;
7438               goto FAILED;
7439               }
7440             recno = recno * 10 + *ptr++ - CHAR_0;
7441             }
7442 
7443           if (*ptr != (pcre_uchar)terminator)
7444             {
7445             *errorcodeptr = ERR29;
7446             goto FAILED;
7447             }
7448 
7449           if (refsign == CHAR_MINUS)
7450             {
7451             if (recno == 0)
7452               {
7453               *errorcodeptr = ERR58;
7454               goto FAILED;
7455               }
7456             recno = cd->bracount - recno + 1;
7457             if (recno <= 0)
7458               {
7459               *errorcodeptr = ERR15;
7460               goto FAILED;
7461               }
7462             }
7463           else if (refsign == CHAR_PLUS)
7464             {
7465             if (recno == 0)
7466               {
7467               *errorcodeptr = ERR58;
7468               goto FAILED;
7469               }
7470             recno += cd->bracount;
7471             }
7472 
7473           /* Come here from code above that handles a named recursion */
7474 
7475           HANDLE_RECURSION:
7476 
7477           previous = code;
7478           item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
7479           called = cd->start_code;
7480 
7481           /* When we are actually compiling, find the bracket that is being
7482           referenced. Temporarily end the regex in case it doesn't exist before
7483           this point. If we end up with a forward reference, first check that
7484           the bracket does occur later so we can give the error (and position)
7485           now. Then remember this forward reference in the workspace so it can
7486           be filled in at the end. */
7487 
7488           if (lengthptr == NULL)
7489             {
7490             *code = OP_END;
7491             if (recno != 0)
7492               called = PRIV(find_bracket)(cd->start_code, utf, recno);
7493 
7494             /* Forward reference */
7495 
7496             if (called == NULL)
7497               {
7498               if (recno > cd->final_bracount)
7499                 {
7500                 *errorcodeptr = ERR15;
7501                 goto FAILED;
7502                 }
7503 
7504               /* Fudge the value of "called" so that when it is inserted as an
7505               offset below, what it actually inserted is the reference number
7506               of the group. Then remember the forward reference. */
7507 
7508               called = cd->start_code + recno;
7509               if (cd->hwm >= cd->start_workspace + cd->workspace_size -
7510                   WORK_SIZE_SAFETY_MARGIN)
7511                 {
7512                 *errorcodeptr = expand_workspace(cd);
7513                 if (*errorcodeptr != 0) goto FAILED;
7514                 }
7515               PUTINC(cd->hwm, 0, (int)(code + 1 - cd->start_code));
7516               }
7517 
7518             /* If not a forward reference, and the subpattern is still open,
7519             this is a recursive call. We check to see if this is a left
7520             recursion that could loop for ever, and diagnose that case. We
7521             must not, however, do this check if we are in a conditional
7522             subpattern because the condition might be testing for recursion in
7523             a pattern such as /(?(R)a+|(?R)b)/, which is perfectly valid.
7524             Forever loops are also detected at runtime, so those that occur in
7525             conditional subpatterns will be picked up then. */
7526 
7527             else if (GET(called, 1) == 0 && cond_depth <= 0 &&
7528                      could_be_empty(called, code, bcptr, utf, cd))
7529               {
7530               *errorcodeptr = ERR40;
7531               goto FAILED;
7532               }
7533             }
7534 
7535           /* Insert the recursion/subroutine item. It does not have a set first
7536           character (relevant if it is repeated, because it will then be
7537           wrapped with ONCE brackets). */
7538 
7539           *code = OP_RECURSE;
7540           PUT(code, 1, (int)(called - cd->start_code));
7541           code += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
7542           groupsetfirstchar = FALSE;
7543           }
7544 
7545         /* Can't determine a first byte now */
7546 
7547         if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET) firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7548         continue;
7549 
7550 
7551         /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */
7552         default:              /* Other characters: check option setting */
7553         OTHER_CHAR_AFTER_QUERY:
7554         set = unset = 0;
7555         optset = &set;
7556 
7557         while (*ptr != CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS && *ptr != CHAR_COLON)
7558           {
7559           switch (*ptr++)
7560             {
7561             case CHAR_MINUS: optset = &unset; break;
7562 
7563             case CHAR_J:    /* Record that it changed in the external options */
7564             *optset |= PCRE_DUPNAMES;
7565             cd->external_flags |= PCRE_JCHANGED;
7566             break;
7567 
7568             case CHAR_i: *optset |= PCRE_CASELESS; break;
7569             case CHAR_m: *optset |= PCRE_MULTILINE; break;
7570             case CHAR_s: *optset |= PCRE_DOTALL; break;
7571             case CHAR_x: *optset |= PCRE_EXTENDED; break;
7572             case CHAR_U: *optset |= PCRE_UNGREEDY; break;
7573             case CHAR_X: *optset |= PCRE_EXTRA; break;
7574 
7575             default:  *errorcodeptr = ERR12;
7576                       ptr--;    /* Correct the offset */
7577                       goto FAILED;
7578             }
7579           }
7580 
7581         /* Set up the changed option bits, but don't change anything yet. */
7582 
7583         newoptions = (options | set) & (~unset);
7584 
7585         /* If the options ended with ')' this is not the start of a nested
7586         group with option changes, so the options change at this level. If this
7587         item is right at the start of the pattern, the options can be
7588         abstracted and made external in the pre-compile phase, and ignored in
7589         the compile phase. This can be helpful when matching -- for instance in
7590         caseless checking of required bytes.
7591 
7592         If the code pointer is not (cd->start_code + 1 + LINK_SIZE), we are
7593         definitely *not* at the start of the pattern because something has been
7594         compiled. In the pre-compile phase, however, the code pointer can have
7595         that value after the start, because it gets reset as code is discarded
7596         during the pre-compile. However, this can happen only at top level - if
7597         we are within parentheses, the starting BRA will still be present. At
7598         any parenthesis level, the length value can be used to test if anything
7599         has been compiled at that level. Thus, a test for both these conditions
7600         is necessary to ensure we correctly detect the start of the pattern in
7601         both phases.
7602 
7603         If we are not at the pattern start, reset the greedy defaults and the
7604         case value for firstchar and reqchar. */
7605 
7606         if (*ptr == CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS)
7607           {
7608           if (code == cd->start_code + 1 + LINK_SIZE &&
7609                (lengthptr == NULL || *lengthptr == 2 + 2*LINK_SIZE))
7610             {
7611             cd->external_options = newoptions;
7612             }
7613           else
7614             {
7615             greedy_default = ((newoptions & PCRE_UNGREEDY) != 0);
7616             greedy_non_default = greedy_default ^ 1;
7617             req_caseopt = ((newoptions & PCRE_CASELESS) != 0)? REQ_CASELESS:0;
7618             }
7619 
7620           /* Change options at this level, and pass them back for use
7621           in subsequent branches. */
7622 
7623           *optionsptr = options = newoptions;
7624           previous = NULL;       /* This item can't be repeated */
7625           continue;              /* It is complete */
7626           }
7627 
7628         /* If the options ended with ':' we are heading into a nested group
7629         with possible change of options. Such groups are non-capturing and are
7630         not assertions of any kind. All we need to do is skip over the ':';
7631         the newoptions value is handled below. */
7632 
7633         bravalue = OP_BRA;
7634         ptr++;
7635         }     /* End of switch for character following (? */
7636       }       /* End of (? handling */
7637 
7638     /* Opening parenthesis not followed by '*' or '?'. If PCRE_NO_AUTO_CAPTURE
7639     is set, all unadorned brackets become non-capturing and behave like (?:...)
7640     brackets. */
7641 
7642     else if ((options & PCRE_NO_AUTO_CAPTURE) != 0)
7643       {
7644       bravalue = OP_BRA;
7645       }
7646 
7647     /* Else we have a capturing group. */
7648 
7649     else
7650       {
7651       NUMBERED_GROUP:
7652       cd->bracount += 1;
7653       PUT2(code, 1+LINK_SIZE, cd->bracount);
7654       skipbytes = IMM2_SIZE;
7655       }
7656 
7657     /* Process nested bracketed regex. First check for parentheses nested too
7658     deeply. */
7659 
7660     if ((cd->parens_depth += 1) > PARENS_NEST_LIMIT)
7661       {
7662       *errorcodeptr = ERR82;
7663       goto FAILED;
7664       }
7665 
7666     /* All assertions used not to be repeatable, but this was changed for Perl
7667     compatibility. All kinds can now be repeated except for assertions that are
7668     conditions (Perl also forbids these to be repeated). We copy code into a
7669     non-register variable (tempcode) in order to be able to pass its address
7670     because some compilers complain otherwise. At the start of a conditional
7671     group whose condition is an assertion, cd->iscondassert is set. We unset it
7672     here so as to allow assertions later in the group to be quantified. */
7673 
7674     if (bravalue >= OP_ASSERT && bravalue <= OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT &&
7675         cd->iscondassert)
7676       {
7677       previous = NULL;
7678       cd->iscondassert = FALSE;
7679       }
7680     else
7681       {
7682       previous = code;
7683       item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
7684       }
7685 
7686     *code = bravalue;
7687     tempcode = code;
7688     tempreqvary = cd->req_varyopt;        /* Save value before bracket */
7689     tempbracount = cd->bracount;          /* Save value before bracket */
7690     length_prevgroup = 0;                 /* Initialize for pre-compile phase */
7691 
7692     if (!compile_regex(
7693          newoptions,                      /* The complete new option state */
7694          &tempcode,                       /* Where to put code (updated) */
7695          &ptr,                            /* Input pointer (updated) */
7696          errorcodeptr,                    /* Where to put an error message */
7697          (bravalue == OP_ASSERTBACK ||
7698           bravalue == OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT), /* TRUE if back assert */
7699          reset_bracount,                  /* True if (?| group */
7700          skipbytes,                       /* Skip over bracket number */
7701          cond_depth +
7702            ((bravalue == OP_COND)?1:0),   /* Depth of condition subpatterns */
7703          &subfirstchar,                   /* For possible first char */
7704          &subfirstcharflags,
7705          &subreqchar,                     /* For possible last char */
7706          &subreqcharflags,
7707          bcptr,                           /* Current branch chain */
7708          cd,                              /* Tables block */
7709          (lengthptr == NULL)? NULL :      /* Actual compile phase */
7710            &length_prevgroup              /* Pre-compile phase */
7711          ))
7712       goto FAILED;
7713 
7714     cd->parens_depth -= 1;
7715 
7716     /* If this was an atomic group and there are no capturing groups within it,
7717     generate OP_ONCE_NC instead of OP_ONCE. */
7718 
7719     if (bravalue == OP_ONCE && cd->bracount <= tempbracount)
7720       *code = OP_ONCE_NC;
7721 
7722     if (bravalue >= OP_ASSERT && bravalue <= OP_ASSERTBACK_NOT)
7723       cd->assert_depth -= 1;
7724 
7725     /* At the end of compiling, code is still pointing to the start of the
7726     group, while tempcode has been updated to point past the end of the group.
7727     The pattern pointer (ptr) is on the bracket.
7728 
7729     If this is a conditional bracket, check that there are no more than
7730     two branches in the group, or just one if it's a DEFINE group. We do this
7731     in the real compile phase, not in the pre-pass, where the whole group may
7732     not be available. */
7733 
7734     if (bravalue == OP_COND && lengthptr == NULL)
7735       {
7736       pcre_uchar *tc = code;
7737       int condcount = 0;
7738 
7739       do {
7740          condcount++;
7741          tc += GET(tc,1);
7742          }
7743       while (*tc != OP_KET);
7744 
7745       /* A DEFINE group is never obeyed inline (the "condition" is always
7746       false). It must have only one branch. */
7747 
7748       if (code[LINK_SIZE+1] == OP_DEF)
7749         {
7750         if (condcount > 1)
7751           {
7752           *errorcodeptr = ERR54;
7753           goto FAILED;
7754           }
7755         bravalue = OP_DEF;   /* Just a flag to suppress char handling below */
7756         }
7757 
7758       /* A "normal" conditional group. If there is just one branch, we must not
7759       make use of its firstchar or reqchar, because this is equivalent to an
7760       empty second branch. */
7761 
7762       else
7763         {
7764         if (condcount > 2)
7765           {
7766           *errorcodeptr = ERR27;
7767           goto FAILED;
7768           }
7769         if (condcount == 1) subfirstcharflags = subreqcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7770         }
7771       }
7772 
7773     /* Error if hit end of pattern */
7774 
7775     if (*ptr != CHAR_RIGHT_PARENTHESIS)
7776       {
7777       *errorcodeptr = ERR14;
7778       goto FAILED;
7779       }
7780 
7781     /* In the pre-compile phase, update the length by the length of the group,
7782     less the brackets at either end. Then reduce the compiled code to just a
7783     set of non-capturing brackets so that it doesn't use much memory if it is
7784     duplicated by a quantifier.*/
7785 
7786     if (lengthptr != NULL)
7787       {
7788       if (OFLOW_MAX - *lengthptr < length_prevgroup - 2 - 2*LINK_SIZE)
7789         {
7790         *errorcodeptr = ERR20;
7791         goto FAILED;
7792         }
7793       *lengthptr += length_prevgroup - 2 - 2*LINK_SIZE;
7794       code++;   /* This already contains bravalue */
7795       PUTINC(code, 0, 1 + LINK_SIZE);
7796       *code++ = OP_KET;
7797       PUTINC(code, 0, 1 + LINK_SIZE);
7798       break;    /* No need to waste time with special character handling */
7799       }
7800 
7801     /* Otherwise update the main code pointer to the end of the group. */
7802 
7803     code = tempcode;
7804 
7805     /* For a DEFINE group, required and first character settings are not
7806     relevant. */
7807 
7808     if (bravalue == OP_DEF) break;
7809 
7810     /* Handle updating of the required and first characters for other types of
7811     group. Update for normal brackets of all kinds, and conditions with two
7812     branches (see code above). If the bracket is followed by a quantifier with
7813     zero repeat, we have to back off. Hence the definition of zeroreqchar and
7814     zerofirstchar outside the main loop so that they can be accessed for the
7815     back off. */
7816 
7817     zeroreqchar = reqchar;
7818     zeroreqcharflags = reqcharflags;
7819     zerofirstchar = firstchar;
7820     zerofirstcharflags = firstcharflags;
7821     groupsetfirstchar = FALSE;
7822 
7823     if (bravalue >= OP_ONCE)
7824       {
7825       /* If we have not yet set a firstchar in this branch, take it from the
7826       subpattern, remembering that it was set here so that a repeat of more
7827       than one can replicate it as reqchar if necessary. If the subpattern has
7828       no firstchar, set "none" for the whole branch. In both cases, a zero
7829       repeat forces firstchar to "none". */
7830 
7831       if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET)
7832         {
7833         if (subfirstcharflags >= 0)
7834           {
7835           firstchar = subfirstchar;
7836           firstcharflags = subfirstcharflags;
7837           groupsetfirstchar = TRUE;
7838           }
7839         else firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7840         zerofirstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7841         }
7842 
7843       /* If firstchar was previously set, convert the subpattern's firstchar
7844       into reqchar if there wasn't one, using the vary flag that was in
7845       existence beforehand. */
7846 
7847       else if (subfirstcharflags >= 0 && subreqcharflags < 0)
7848         {
7849         subreqchar = subfirstchar;
7850         subreqcharflags = subfirstcharflags | tempreqvary;
7851         }
7852 
7853       /* If the subpattern set a required byte (or set a first byte that isn't
7854       really the first byte - see above), set it. */
7855 
7856       if (subreqcharflags >= 0)
7857         {
7858         reqchar = subreqchar;
7859         reqcharflags = subreqcharflags;
7860         }
7861       }
7862 
7863     /* For a forward assertion, we take the reqchar, if set. This can be
7864     helpful if the pattern that follows the assertion doesn't set a different
7865     char. For example, it's useful for /(?=abcde).+/. We can't set firstchar
7866     for an assertion, however because it leads to incorrect effect for patterns
7867     such as /(?=a)a.+/ when the "real" "a" would then become a reqchar instead
7868     of a firstchar. This is overcome by a scan at the end if there's no
7869     firstchar, looking for an asserted first char. */
7870 
7871     else if (bravalue == OP_ASSERT && subreqcharflags >= 0)
7872       {
7873       reqchar = subreqchar;
7874       reqcharflags = subreqcharflags;
7875       }
7876     break;     /* End of processing '(' */
7877 
7878 
7879     /* ===================================================================*/
7880     /* Handle metasequences introduced by \. For ones like \d, the ESC_ values
7881     are arranged to be the negation of the corresponding OP_values in the
7882     default case when PCRE_UCP is not set. For the back references, the values
7883     are negative the reference number. Only back references and those types
7884     that consume a character may be repeated. We can test for values between
7885     ESC_b and ESC_Z for the latter; this may have to change if any new ones are
7886     ever created. */
7887 
7888     case CHAR_BACKSLASH:
7889     tempptr = ptr;
7890     escape = check_escape(&ptr, &ec, errorcodeptr, cd->bracount, options, FALSE);
7891     if (*errorcodeptr != 0) goto FAILED;
7892 
7893     if (escape == 0)                  /* The escape coded a single character */
7894       c = ec;
7895     else
7896       {
7897       if (escape == ESC_Q)            /* Handle start of quoted string */
7898         {
7899         if (ptr[1] == CHAR_BACKSLASH && ptr[2] == CHAR_E)
7900           ptr += 2;               /* avoid empty string */
7901             else inescq = TRUE;
7902         continue;
7903         }
7904 
7905       if (escape == ESC_E) continue;  /* Perl ignores an orphan \E */
7906 
7907       /* For metasequences that actually match a character, we disable the
7908       setting of a first character if it hasn't already been set. */
7909 
7910       if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET && escape > ESC_b && escape < ESC_Z)
7911         firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7912 
7913       /* Set values to reset to if this is followed by a zero repeat. */
7914 
7915       zerofirstchar = firstchar;
7916       zerofirstcharflags = firstcharflags;
7917       zeroreqchar = reqchar;
7918       zeroreqcharflags = reqcharflags;
7919 
7920       /* \g<name> or \g'name' is a subroutine call by name and \g<n> or \g'n'
7921       is a subroutine call by number (Oniguruma syntax). In fact, the value
7922       ESC_g is returned only for these cases. So we don't need to check for <
7923       or ' if the value is ESC_g. For the Perl syntax \g{n} the value is
7924       -n, and for the Perl syntax \g{name} the result is ESC_k (as
7925       that is a synonym for a named back reference). */
7926 
7927       if (escape == ESC_g)
7928         {
7929         const pcre_uchar *p;
7930         pcre_uint32 cf;
7931 
7932         item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;   /* Normally this is set when '(' is read */
7933         terminator = (*(++ptr) == CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN)?
7934           CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN : CHAR_APOSTROPHE;
7935 
7936         /* These two statements stop the compiler for warning about possibly
7937         unset variables caused by the jump to HANDLE_NUMERICAL_RECURSION. In
7938         fact, because we do the check for a number below, the paths that
7939         would actually be in error are never taken. */
7940 
7941         skipbytes = 0;
7942         reset_bracount = FALSE;
7943 
7944         /* If it's not a signed or unsigned number, treat it as a name. */
7945 
7946         cf = ptr[1];
7947         if (cf != CHAR_PLUS && cf != CHAR_MINUS && !IS_DIGIT(cf))
7948           {
7949           is_recurse = TRUE;
7950           goto NAMED_REF_OR_RECURSE;
7951           }
7952 
7953         /* Signed or unsigned number (cf = ptr[1]) is known to be plus or minus
7954         or a digit. */
7955 
7956         p = ptr + 2;
7957         while (IS_DIGIT(*p)) p++;
7958         if (*p != (pcre_uchar)terminator)
7959           {
7960           *errorcodeptr = ERR57;
7961           goto FAILED;
7962           }
7963         ptr++;
7964         goto HANDLE_NUMERICAL_RECURSION;
7965         }
7966 
7967       /* \k<name> or \k'name' is a back reference by name (Perl syntax).
7968       We also support \k{name} (.NET syntax).  */
7969 
7970       if (escape == ESC_k)
7971         {
7972         if ((ptr[1] != CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN &&
7973           ptr[1] != CHAR_APOSTROPHE && ptr[1] != CHAR_LEFT_CURLY_BRACKET))
7974           {
7975           *errorcodeptr = ERR69;
7976           goto FAILED;
7977           }
7978         is_recurse = FALSE;
7979         terminator = (*(++ptr) == CHAR_LESS_THAN_SIGN)?
7980           CHAR_GREATER_THAN_SIGN : (*ptr == CHAR_APOSTROPHE)?
7981           CHAR_APOSTROPHE : CHAR_RIGHT_CURLY_BRACKET;
7982         goto NAMED_REF_OR_RECURSE;
7983         }
7984 
7985       /* Back references are handled specially; must disable firstchar if
7986       not set to cope with cases like (?=(\w+))\1: which would otherwise set
7987       ':' later. */
7988 
7989       if (escape < 0)
7990         {
7991         open_capitem *oc;
7992         recno = -escape;
7993 
7994         /* Come here from named backref handling when the reference is to a
7995         single group (i.e. not to a duplicated name. */
7996 
7997         HANDLE_REFERENCE:
7998         if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET) firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
7999         previous = code;
8000         item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
8001         *code++ = ((options & PCRE_CASELESS) != 0)? OP_REFI : OP_REF;
8002         PUT2INC(code, 0, recno);
8003         cd->backref_map |= (recno < 32)? (1 << recno) : 1;
8004         if (recno > cd->top_backref) cd->top_backref = recno;
8005 
8006         /* Check to see if this back reference is recursive, that it, it
8007         is inside the group that it references. A flag is set so that the
8008         group can be made atomic. */
8009 
8010         for (oc = cd->open_caps; oc != NULL; oc = oc->next)
8011           {
8012           if (oc->number == recno)
8013             {
8014             oc->flag = TRUE;
8015             break;
8016             }
8017           }
8018         }
8019 
8020       /* So are Unicode property matches, if supported. */
8021 
8022 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
8023       else if (escape == ESC_P || escape == ESC_p)
8024         {
8025         BOOL negated;
8026         unsigned int ptype = 0, pdata = 0;
8027         if (!get_ucp(&ptr, &negated, &ptype, &pdata, errorcodeptr))
8028           goto FAILED;
8029         previous = code;
8030         item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
8031         *code++ = ((escape == ESC_p) != negated)? OP_PROP : OP_NOTPROP;
8032         *code++ = ptype;
8033         *code++ = pdata;
8034         }
8035 #else
8036 
8037       /* If Unicode properties are not supported, \X, \P, and \p are not
8038       allowed. */
8039 
8040       else if (escape == ESC_X || escape == ESC_P || escape == ESC_p)
8041         {
8042         *errorcodeptr = ERR45;
8043         goto FAILED;
8044         }
8045 #endif
8046 
8047       /* For the rest (including \X when Unicode properties are supported), we
8048       can obtain the OP value by negating the escape value in the default
8049       situation when PCRE_UCP is not set. When it *is* set, we substitute
8050       Unicode property tests. Note that \b and \B do a one-character
8051       lookbehind, and \A also behaves as if it does. */
8052 
8053       else
8054         {
8055         if ((escape == ESC_b || escape == ESC_B || escape == ESC_A) &&
8056              cd->max_lookbehind == 0)
8057           cd->max_lookbehind = 1;
8058 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
8059         if (escape >= ESC_DU && escape <= ESC_wu)
8060           {
8061           nestptr = ptr + 1;                   /* Where to resume */
8062           ptr = substitutes[escape - ESC_DU] - 1;  /* Just before substitute */
8063           }
8064         else
8065 #endif
8066         /* In non-UTF-8 mode, we turn \C into OP_ALLANY instead of OP_ANYBYTE
8067         so that it works in DFA mode and in lookbehinds. */
8068 
8069           {
8070           previous = (escape > ESC_b && escape < ESC_Z)? code : NULL;
8071           item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
8072           *code++ = (!utf && escape == ESC_C)? OP_ALLANY : escape;
8073           }
8074         }
8075       continue;
8076       }
8077 
8078     /* We have a data character whose value is in c. In UTF-8 mode it may have
8079     a value > 127. We set its representation in the length/buffer, and then
8080     handle it as a data character. */
8081 
8082 #if defined SUPPORT_UTF && !defined COMPILE_PCRE32
8083     if (utf && c > MAX_VALUE_FOR_SINGLE_CHAR)
8084       mclength = PRIV(ord2utf)(c, mcbuffer);
8085     else
8086 #endif
8087 
8088      {
8089      mcbuffer[0] = c;
8090      mclength = 1;
8091      }
8092     goto ONE_CHAR;
8093 
8094 
8095     /* ===================================================================*/
8096     /* Handle a literal character. It is guaranteed not to be whitespace or #
8097     when the extended flag is set. If we are in a UTF mode, it may be a
8098     multi-unit literal character. */
8099 
8100     default:
8101     NORMAL_CHAR:
8102     mclength = 1;
8103     mcbuffer[0] = c;
8104 
8105 #ifdef SUPPORT_UTF
8106     if (utf && HAS_EXTRALEN(c))
8107       ACROSSCHAR(TRUE, ptr[1], mcbuffer[mclength++] = *(++ptr));
8108 #endif
8109 
8110     /* At this point we have the character's bytes in mcbuffer, and the length
8111     in mclength. When not in UTF-8 mode, the length is always 1. */
8112 
8113     ONE_CHAR:
8114     previous = code;
8115     item_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
8116 
8117     /* For caseless UTF-8 mode when UCP support is available, check whether
8118     this character has more than one other case. If so, generate a special
8119     OP_PROP item instead of OP_CHARI. */
8120 
8121 #ifdef SUPPORT_UCP
8122     if (utf && (options & PCRE_CASELESS) != 0)
8123       {
8124       GETCHAR(c, mcbuffer);
8125       if ((c = UCD_CASESET(c)) != 0)
8126         {
8127         *code++ = OP_PROP;
8128         *code++ = PT_CLIST;
8129         *code++ = c;
8130         if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET)
8131           firstcharflags = zerofirstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
8132         break;
8133         }
8134       }
8135 #endif
8136 
8137     /* Caseful matches, or not one of the multicase characters. */
8138 
8139     *code++ = ((options & PCRE_CASELESS) != 0)? OP_CHARI : OP_CHAR;
8140     for (c = 0; c < mclength; c++) *code++ = mcbuffer[c];
8141 
8142     /* Remember if \r or \n were seen */
8143 
8144     if (mcbuffer[0] == CHAR_CR || mcbuffer[0] == CHAR_NL)
8145       cd->external_flags |= PCRE_HASCRORLF;
8146 
8147     /* Set the first and required bytes appropriately. If no previous first
8148     byte, set it from this character, but revert to none on a zero repeat.
8149     Otherwise, leave the firstchar value alone, and don't change it on a zero
8150     repeat. */
8151 
8152     if (firstcharflags == REQ_UNSET)
8153       {
8154       zerofirstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
8155       zeroreqchar = reqchar;
8156       zeroreqcharflags = reqcharflags;
8157 
8158       /* If the character is more than one byte long, we can set firstchar
8159       only if it is not to be matched caselessly. */
8160 
8161       if (mclength == 1 || req_caseopt == 0)
8162         {
8163         firstchar = mcbuffer[0] | req_caseopt;
8164         firstchar = mcbuffer[0];
8165         firstcharflags = req_caseopt;
8166 
8167         if (mclength != 1)
8168           {
8169           reqchar = code[-1];
8170           reqcharflags = cd->req_varyopt;
8171           }
8172         }
8173       else firstcharflags = reqcharflags = REQ_NONE;
8174       }
8175 
8176     /* firstchar was previously set; we can set reqchar only if the length is
8177     1 or the matching is caseful. */
8178 
8179     else
8180       {
8181       zerofirstchar = firstchar;
8182       zerofirstcharflags = firstcharflags;
8183       zeroreqchar = reqchar;
8184       zeroreqcharflags = reqcharflags;
8185       if (mclength == 1 || req_caseopt == 0)
8186         {
8187         reqchar = code[-1];
8188         reqcharflags = req_caseopt | cd->req_varyopt;
8189         }
8190       }
8191 
8192     break;            /* End of literal character handling */
8193     }
8194   }                   /* end of big loop */
8195 
8196 
8197 /* Control never reaches here by falling through, only by a goto for all the
8198 error states. Pass back the position in the pattern so that it can be displayed
8199 to the user for diagnosing the error. */
8200 
8201 FAILED:
8202 *ptrptr = ptr;
8203 return FALSE;
8204 }
8205 
8206 
8207 
8208 /*************************************************
8209 *     Compile sequence of alternatives           *
8210 *************************************************/
8211 
8212 /* On entry, ptr is pointing past the bracket character, but on return it
8213 points to the closing bracket, or vertical bar, or end of string. The code
8214 variable is pointing at the byte into which the BRA operator has been stored.
8215 This function is used during the pre-compile phase when we are trying to find
8216 out the amount of memory needed, as well as during the real compile phase. The
8217 value of lengthptr distinguishes the two phases.
8218 
8219 Arguments:
8220   options           option bits, including any changes for this subpattern
8221   codeptr           -> the address of the current code pointer
8222   ptrptr            -> the address of the current pattern pointer
8223   errorcodeptr      -> pointer to error code variable
8224   lookbehind        TRUE if this is a lookbehind assertion
8225   reset_bracount    TRUE to reset the count for each branch
8226   skipbytes         skip this many bytes at start (for brackets and OP_COND)
8227   cond_depth        depth of nesting for conditional subpatterns
8228   firstcharptr      place to put the first required character
8229   firstcharflagsptr place to put the first character flags, or a negative number
8230   reqcharptr        place to put the last required character
8231   reqcharflagsptr   place to put the last required character flags, or a negative number
8232   bcptr             pointer to the chain of currently open branches
8233   cd                points to the data block with tables pointers etc.
8234   lengthptr         NULL during the real compile phase
8235                     points to length accumulator during pre-compile phase
8236 
8237 Returns:            TRUE on success
8238 */
8239 
8240 static BOOL
8241 compile_regex(int options, pcre_uchar **codeptr, const pcre_uchar **ptrptr,
8242   int *errorcodeptr, BOOL lookbehind, BOOL reset_bracount, int skipbytes,
8243   int cond_depth,
8244   pcre_uint32 *firstcharptr, pcre_int32 *firstcharflagsptr,
8245   pcre_uint32 *reqcharptr, pcre_int32 *reqcharflagsptr,
8246   branch_chain *bcptr, compile_data *cd, int *lengthptr)
8247 {
8248 const pcre_uchar *ptr = *ptrptr;
8249 pcre_uchar *code = *codeptr;
8250 pcre_uchar *last_branch = code;
8251 pcre_uchar *start_bracket = code;
8252 pcre_uchar *reverse_count = NULL;
8253 open_capitem capitem;
8254 int capnumber = 0;
8255 pcre_uint32 firstchar, reqchar;
8256 pcre_int32 firstcharflags, reqcharflags;
8257 pcre_uint32 branchfirstchar, branchreqchar;
8258 pcre_int32 branchfirstcharflags, branchreqcharflags;
8259 int length;
8260 unsigned int orig_bracount;
8261 unsigned int max_bracount;
8262 branch_chain bc;
8263 size_t save_hwm_offset;
8264 
8265 /* If set, call the external function that checks for stack availability. */
8266 
8267 if (PUBL(stack_guard) != NULL && PUBL(stack_guard)())
8268   {
8269   *errorcodeptr= ERR85;
8270   return FALSE;
8271   }
8272 
8273 /* Miscellaneous initialization */
8274 
8275 bc.outer = bcptr;
8276 bc.current_branch = code;
8277 
8278 firstchar = reqchar = 0;
8279 firstcharflags = reqcharflags = REQ_UNSET;
8280 
8281 save_hwm_offset = cd->hwm - cd->start_workspace;
8282 
8283 /* Accumulate the length for use in the pre-compile phase. Start with the
8284 length of the BRA and KET and any extra bytes that are required at the
8285 beginning. We accumulate in a local variable to save frequent testing of
8286 lenthptr for NULL. We cannot do this by looking at the value of code at the
8287 start and end of each alternative, because compiled items are discarded during
8288 the pre-compile phase so that the work space is not exceeded. */
8289 
8290 length = 2 + 2*LINK_SIZE + skipbytes;
8291 
8292 /* WARNING: If the above line is changed for any reason, you must also change
8293 the code that abstracts option settings at the start of the pattern and makes
8294 them global. It tests the value of length for (2 + 2*LINK_SIZE) in the
8295 pre-compile phase to find out whether anything has yet been compiled or not. */
8296 
8297 /* If this is a capturing subpattern, add to the chain of open capturing items
8298 so that we can detect them if (*ACCEPT) is encountered. This is also used to
8299 detect groups that contain recursive back references to themselves. Note that
8300 only OP_CBRA need be tested here; changing this opcode to one of its variants,
8301 e.g. OP_SCBRAPOS, happens later, after the group has been compiled. */
8302 
8303 if (*code == OP_CBRA)
8304   {
8305   capnumber = GET2(code, 1 + LINK_SIZE);
8306   capitem.number = capnumber;
8307   capitem.next = cd->open_caps;
8308   capitem.flag = FALSE;
8309   cd->open_caps = &capitem;
8310   }
8311 
8312 /* Offset is set zero to mark that this bracket is still open */
8313 
8314 PUT(code, 1, 0);
8315 code += 1 + LINK_SIZE + skipbytes;
8316 
8317 /* Loop for each alternative branch */
8318 
8319 orig_bracount = max_bracount = cd->bracount;
8320 for (;;)
8321   {
8322   /* For a (?| group, reset the capturing bracket count so that each branch
8323   uses the same numbers. */
8324 
8325   if (reset_bracount) cd->bracount = orig_bracount;
8326 
8327   /* Set up dummy OP_REVERSE if lookbehind assertion */
8328 
8329   if (lookbehind)
8330     {
8331     *code++ = OP_REVERSE;
8332     reverse_count = code;
8333     PUTINC(code, 0, 0);
8334     length += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8335     }
8336 
8337   /* Now compile the branch; in the pre-compile phase its length gets added
8338   into the length. */
8339 
8340   if (!compile_branch(&options, &code, &ptr, errorcodeptr, &branchfirstchar,
8341         &branchfirstcharflags, &branchreqchar, &branchreqcharflags, &bc,
8342         cond_depth, cd, (lengthptr == NULL)? NULL : &length))
8343     {
8344     *ptrptr = ptr;
8345     return FALSE;
8346     }
8347 
8348   /* Keep the highest bracket count in case (?| was used and some branch
8349   has fewer than the rest. */
8350 
8351   if (cd->bracount > max_bracount) max_bracount = cd->bracount;
8352 
8353   /* In the real compile phase, there is some post-processing to be done. */
8354 
8355   if (lengthptr == NULL)
8356     {
8357     /* If this is the first branch, the firstchar and reqchar values for the
8358     branch become the values for the regex. */
8359 
8360     if (*last_branch != OP_ALT)
8361       {
8362       firstchar = branchfirstchar;
8363       firstcharflags = branchfirstcharflags;
8364       reqchar = branchreqchar;
8365       reqcharflags = branchreqcharflags;
8366       }
8367 
8368     /* If this is not the first branch, the first char and reqchar have to
8369     match the values from all the previous branches, except that if the
8370     previous value for reqchar didn't have REQ_VARY set, it can still match,
8371     and we set REQ_VARY for the regex. */
8372 
8373     else
8374       {
8375       /* If we previously had a firstchar, but it doesn't match the new branch,
8376       we have to abandon the firstchar for the regex, but if there was
8377       previously no reqchar, it takes on the value of the old firstchar. */
8378 
8379       if (firstcharflags >= 0 &&
8380           (firstcharflags != branchfirstcharflags || firstchar != branchfirstchar))
8381         {
8382         if (reqcharflags < 0)
8383           {
8384           reqchar = firstchar;
8385           reqcharflags = firstcharflags;
8386           }
8387         firstcharflags = REQ_NONE;
8388         }
8389 
8390       /* If we (now or from before) have no firstchar, a firstchar from the
8391       branch becomes a reqchar if there isn't a branch reqchar. */
8392 
8393       if (firstcharflags < 0 && branchfirstcharflags >= 0 && branchreqcharflags < 0)
8394         {
8395         branchreqchar = branchfirstchar;
8396         branchreqcharflags = branchfirstcharflags;
8397         }
8398 
8399       /* Now ensure that the reqchars match */
8400 
8401       if (((reqcharflags & ~REQ_VARY) != (branchreqcharflags & ~REQ_VARY)) ||
8402           reqchar != branchreqchar)
8403         reqcharflags = REQ_NONE;
8404       else
8405         {
8406         reqchar = branchreqchar;
8407         reqcharflags |= branchreqcharflags; /* To "or" REQ_VARY */
8408         }
8409       }
8410 
8411     /* If lookbehind, check that this branch matches a fixed-length string, and
8412     put the length into the OP_REVERSE item. Temporarily mark the end of the
8413     branch with OP_END. If the branch contains OP_RECURSE, the result is -3
8414     because there may be forward references that we can't check here. Set a
8415     flag to cause another lookbehind check at the end. Why not do it all at the
8416     end? Because common, erroneous checks are picked up here and the offset of
8417     the problem can be shown. */
8418 
8419     if (lookbehind)
8420       {
8421       int fixed_length;
8422       *code = OP_END;
8423       fixed_length = find_fixedlength(last_branch,  (options & PCRE_UTF8) != 0,
8424         FALSE, cd, NULL);
8425       DPRINTF(("fixed length = %d\n", fixed_length));
8426       if (fixed_length == -3)
8427         {
8428         cd->check_lookbehind = TRUE;
8429         }
8430       else if (fixed_length < 0)
8431         {
8432         *errorcodeptr = (fixed_length == -2)? ERR36 :
8433                         (fixed_length == -4)? ERR70: ERR25;
8434         *ptrptr = ptr;
8435         return FALSE;
8436         }
8437       else
8438         {
8439         if (fixed_length > cd->max_lookbehind)
8440           cd->max_lookbehind = fixed_length;
8441         PUT(reverse_count, 0, fixed_length);
8442         }
8443       }
8444     }
8445 
8446   /* Reached end of expression, either ')' or end of pattern. In the real
8447   compile phase, go back through the alternative branches and reverse the chain
8448   of offsets, with the field in the BRA item now becoming an offset to the
8449   first alternative. If there are no alternatives, it points to the end of the
8450   group. The length in the terminating ket is always the length of the whole
8451   bracketed item. Return leaving the pointer at the terminating char. */
8452 
8453   if (*ptr != CHAR_VERTICAL_LINE)
8454     {
8455     if (lengthptr == NULL)
8456       {
8457       int branch_length = (int)(code - last_branch);
8458       do
8459         {
8460         int prev_length = GET(last_branch, 1);
8461         PUT(last_branch, 1, branch_length);
8462         branch_length = prev_length;
8463         last_branch -= branch_length;
8464         }
8465       while (branch_length > 0);
8466       }
8467 
8468     /* Fill in the ket */
8469 
8470     *code = OP_KET;
8471     PUT(code, 1, (int)(code - start_bracket));
8472     code += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8473 
8474     /* If it was a capturing subpattern, check to see if it contained any
8475     recursive back references. If so, we must wrap it in atomic brackets.
8476     Because we are moving code along, we must ensure that any pending recursive
8477     references are updated. In any event, remove the block from the chain. */
8478 
8479     if (capnumber > 0)
8480       {
8481       if (cd->open_caps->flag)
8482         {
8483         *code = OP_END;
8484         adjust_recurse(start_bracket, 1 + LINK_SIZE,
8485           (options & PCRE_UTF8) != 0, cd, save_hwm_offset);
8486         memmove(start_bracket + 1 + LINK_SIZE, start_bracket,
8487           IN_UCHARS(code - start_bracket));
8488         *start_bracket = OP_ONCE;
8489         code += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8490         PUT(start_bracket, 1, (int)(code - start_bracket));
8491         *code = OP_KET;
8492         PUT(code, 1, (int)(code - start_bracket));
8493         code += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8494         length += 2 + 2*LINK_SIZE;
8495         }
8496       cd->open_caps = cd->open_caps->next;
8497       }
8498 
8499     /* Retain the highest bracket number, in case resetting was used. */
8500 
8501     cd->bracount = max_bracount;
8502 
8503     /* Set values to pass back */
8504 
8505     *codeptr = code;
8506     *ptrptr = ptr;
8507     *firstcharptr = firstchar;
8508     *firstcharflagsptr = firstcharflags;
8509     *reqcharptr = reqchar;
8510     *reqcharflagsptr = reqcharflags;
8511     if (lengthptr != NULL)
8512       {
8513       if (OFLOW_MAX - *lengthptr < length)
8514         {
8515         *errorcodeptr = ERR20;
8516         return FALSE;
8517         }
8518       *lengthptr += length;
8519       }
8520     return TRUE;
8521     }
8522 
8523   /* Another branch follows. In the pre-compile phase, we can move the code
8524   pointer back to where it was for the start of the first branch. (That is,
8525   pretend that each branch is the only one.)
8526 
8527   In the real compile phase, insert an ALT node. Its length field points back
8528   to the previous branch while the bracket remains open. At the end the chain
8529   is reversed. It's done like this so that the start of the bracket has a
8530   zero offset until it is closed, making it possible to detect recursion. */
8531 
8532   if (lengthptr != NULL)
8533     {
8534     code = *codeptr + 1 + LINK_SIZE + skipbytes;
8535     length += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8536     }
8537   else
8538     {
8539     *code = OP_ALT;
8540     PUT(code, 1, (int)(code - last_branch));
8541     bc.current_branch = last_branch = code;
8542     code += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8543     }
8544 
8545   ptr++;
8546   }
8547 /* Control never reaches here */
8548 }
8549 
8550 
8551 
8552 
8553 /*************************************************
8554 *          Check for anchored expression         *
8555 *************************************************/
8556 
8557 /* Try to find out if this is an anchored regular expression. Consider each
8558 alternative branch. If they all start with OP_SOD or OP_CIRC, or with a bracket
8559 all of whose alternatives start with OP_SOD or OP_CIRC (recurse ad lib), then
8560 it's anchored. However, if this is a multiline pattern, then only OP_SOD will
8561 be found, because ^ generates OP_CIRCM in that mode.
8562 
8563 We can also consider a regex to be anchored if OP_SOM starts all its branches.
8564 This is the code for \G, which means "match at start of match position, taking
8565 into account the match offset".
8566 
8567 A branch is also implicitly anchored if it starts with .* and DOTALL is set,
8568 because that will try the rest of the pattern at all possible matching points,
8569 so there is no point trying again.... er ....
8570 
8571 .... except when the .* appears inside capturing parentheses, and there is a
8572 subsequent back reference to those parentheses. We haven't enough information
8573 to catch that case precisely.
8574 
8575 At first, the best we could do was to detect when .* was in capturing brackets
8576 and the highest back reference was greater than or equal to that level.
8577 However, by keeping a bitmap of the first 31 back references, we can catch some
8578 of the more common cases more precisely.
8579 
8580 ... A second exception is when the .* appears inside an atomic group, because
8581 this prevents the number of characters it matches from being adjusted.
8582 
8583 Arguments:
8584   code           points to start of expression (the bracket)
8585   bracket_map    a bitmap of which brackets we are inside while testing; this
8586                   handles up to substring 31; after that we just have to take
8587                   the less precise approach
8588   cd             points to the compile data block
8589   atomcount      atomic group level
8590 
8591 Returns:     TRUE or FALSE
8592 */
8593 
8594 static BOOL
8595 is_anchored(register const pcre_uchar *code, unsigned int bracket_map,
8596   compile_data *cd, int atomcount)
8597 {
8598 do {
8599    const pcre_uchar *scode = first_significant_code(
8600      code + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*code], FALSE);
8601    register int op = *scode;
8602 
8603    /* Non-capturing brackets */
8604 
8605    if (op == OP_BRA  || op == OP_BRAPOS ||
8606        op == OP_SBRA || op == OP_SBRAPOS)
8607      {
8608      if (!is_anchored(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8609      }
8610 
8611    /* Capturing brackets */
8612 
8613    else if (op == OP_CBRA  || op == OP_CBRAPOS ||
8614             op == OP_SCBRA || op == OP_SCBRAPOS)
8615      {
8616      int n = GET2(scode, 1+LINK_SIZE);
8617      int new_map = bracket_map | ((n < 32)? (1 << n) : 1);
8618      if (!is_anchored(scode, new_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8619      }
8620 
8621    /* Positive forward assertions and conditions */
8622 
8623    else if (op == OP_ASSERT || op == OP_COND)
8624      {
8625      if (!is_anchored(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8626      }
8627 
8628    /* Atomic groups */
8629 
8630    else if (op == OP_ONCE || op == OP_ONCE_NC)
8631      {
8632      if (!is_anchored(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount + 1))
8633        return FALSE;
8634      }
8635 
8636    /* .* is not anchored unless DOTALL is set (which generates OP_ALLANY) and
8637    it isn't in brackets that are or may be referenced or inside an atomic
8638    group. */
8639 
8640    else if ((op == OP_TYPESTAR || op == OP_TYPEMINSTAR ||
8641              op == OP_TYPEPOSSTAR))
8642      {
8643      if (scode[1] != OP_ALLANY || (bracket_map & cd->backref_map) != 0 ||
8644          atomcount > 0 || cd->had_pruneorskip)
8645        return FALSE;
8646      }
8647 
8648    /* Check for explicit anchoring */
8649 
8650    else if (op != OP_SOD && op != OP_SOM && op != OP_CIRC) return FALSE;
8651 
8652    code += GET(code, 1);
8653    }
8654 while (*code == OP_ALT);   /* Loop for each alternative */
8655 return TRUE;
8656 }
8657 
8658 
8659 
8660 /*************************************************
8661 *         Check for starting with ^ or .*        *
8662 *************************************************/
8663 
8664 /* This is called to find out if every branch starts with ^ or .* so that
8665 "first char" processing can be done to speed things up in multiline
8666 matching and for non-DOTALL patterns that start with .* (which must start at
8667 the beginning or after \n). As in the case of is_anchored() (see above), we
8668 have to take account of back references to capturing brackets that contain .*
8669 because in that case we can't make the assumption. Also, the appearance of .*
8670 inside atomic brackets or in a pattern that contains *PRUNE or *SKIP does not
8671 count, because once again the assumption no longer holds.
8672 
8673 Arguments:
8674   code           points to start of expression (the bracket)
8675   bracket_map    a bitmap of which brackets we are inside while testing; this
8676                   handles up to substring 31; after that we just have to take
8677                   the less precise approach
8678   cd             points to the compile data
8679   atomcount      atomic group level
8680 
8681 Returns:         TRUE or FALSE
8682 */
8683 
8684 static BOOL
8685 is_startline(const pcre_uchar *code, unsigned int bracket_map,
8686   compile_data *cd, int atomcount)
8687 {
8688 do {
8689    const pcre_uchar *scode = first_significant_code(
8690      code + PRIV(OP_lengths)[*code], FALSE);
8691    register int op = *scode;
8692 
8693    /* If we are at the start of a conditional assertion group, *both* the
8694    conditional assertion *and* what follows the condition must satisfy the test
8695    for start of line. Other kinds of condition fail. Note that there may be an
8696    auto-callout at the start of a condition. */
8697 
8698    if (op == OP_COND)
8699      {
8700      scode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8701      if (*scode == OP_CALLOUT) scode += PRIV(OP_lengths)[OP_CALLOUT];
8702      switch (*scode)
8703        {
8704        case OP_CREF:
8705        case OP_DNCREF:
8706        case OP_RREF:
8707        case OP_DNRREF:
8708        case OP_DEF:
8709        case OP_FAIL:
8710        return FALSE;
8711 
8712        default:     /* Assertion */
8713        if (!is_startline(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8714        do scode += GET(scode, 1); while (*scode == OP_ALT);
8715        scode += 1 + LINK_SIZE;
8716        break;
8717        }
8718      scode = first_significant_code(scode, FALSE);
8719      op = *scode;
8720      }
8721 
8722    /* Non-capturing brackets */
8723 
8724    if (op == OP_BRA  || op == OP_BRAPOS ||
8725        op == OP_SBRA || op == OP_SBRAPOS)
8726      {
8727      if (!is_startline(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8728      }
8729 
8730    /* Capturing brackets */
8731 
8732    else if (op == OP_CBRA  || op == OP_CBRAPOS ||
8733             op == OP_SCBRA || op == OP_SCBRAPOS)
8734      {
8735      int n = GET2(scode, 1+LINK_SIZE);
8736      int new_map = bracket_map | ((n < 32)? (1 << n) : 1);
8737      if (!is_startline(scode, new_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8738      }
8739 
8740    /* Positive forward assertions */
8741 
8742    else if (op == OP_ASSERT)
8743      {
8744      if (!is_startline(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount)) return FALSE;
8745      }
8746 
8747    /* Atomic brackets */
8748 
8749    else if (op == OP_ONCE || op == OP_ONCE_NC)
8750      {
8751      if (!is_startline(scode, bracket_map, cd, atomcount + 1)) return FALSE;
8752      }
8753 
8754    /* .* means "start at start or after \n" if it isn't in atomic brackets or
8755    brackets that may be referenced, as long as the pattern does not contain
8756    *PRUNE or *SKIP, because these break the feature. Consider, for example,
8757    /.*?a(*PRUNE)b/ with the subject "aab", which matches "ab", i.e. not at the
8758    start of a line. */
8759 
8760    else if (op == OP_TYPESTAR || op == OP_TYPEMINSTAR || op == OP_TYPEPOSSTAR)
8761      {
8762      if (scode[1] != OP_ANY || (bracket_map & cd->backref_map) != 0 ||
8763          atomcount > 0 || cd->had_pruneorskip)
8764        return FALSE;
8765      }
8766 
8767    /* Check for explicit circumflex; anything else gives a FALSE result. Note
8768    in particular that this includes atomic brackets OP_ONCE and OP_ONCE_NC
8769    because the number of characters matched by .* cannot be adjusted inside
8770    them. */
8771 
8772    else if (op != OP_CIRC && op != OP_CIRCM) return FALSE;
8773 
8774    /* Move on to the next alternative */
8775 
8776    code += GET(code, 1);
8777    }
8778 while (*code == OP_ALT);  /* Loop for each alternative */
8779 return TRUE;
8780 }
8781 
8782 
8783 
8784 /*************************************************
8785 *       Check for asserted fixed first char      *
8786 *************************************************/
8787 
8788 /* During compilation, the "first char" settings from forward assertions are
8789 discarded, because they can cause conflicts with actual literals that follow.
8790 However, if we end up without a first char setting for an unanchored pattern,
8791 it is worth scanning the regex to see if there is an initial asserted first
8792 char. If all branches start with the same asserted char, or with a
8793 non-conditional bracket all of whose alternatives start with the same asserted
8794 char (recurse ad lib), then we return that char, with the flags set to zero or
8795 REQ_CASELESS; otherwise return zero with REQ_NONE in the flags.
8796 
8797 Arguments:
8798   code       points to start of expression (the bracket)
8799   flags      points to the first char flags, or to REQ_NONE
8800   inassert   TRUE if in an assertion
8801 
8802 Returns:     the fixed first char, or 0 with REQ_NONE in flags
8803 */
8804 
8805 static pcre_uint32
8806 find_firstassertedchar(const pcre_uchar *code, pcre_int32 *flags,
8807   BOOL inassert)
8808 {
8809 register pcre_uint32 c = 0;
8810 int cflags = REQ_NONE;
8811 
8812 *flags = REQ_NONE;
8813 do {
8814    pcre_uint32 d;
8815    int dflags;
8816    int xl = (*code == OP_CBRA || *code == OP_SCBRA ||
8817              *code == OP_CBRAPOS || *code == OP_SCBRAPOS)? IMM2_SIZE:0;
8818    const pcre_uchar *scode = first_significant_code(code + 1+LINK_SIZE + xl,
8819      TRUE);
8820    register pcre_uchar op = *scode;
8821 
8822    switch(op)
8823      {
8824      default:
8825      return 0;
8826 
8827      case OP_BRA:
8828      case OP_BRAPOS:
8829      case OP_CBRA:
8830      case OP_SCBRA:
8831      case OP_CBRAPOS:
8832      case OP_SCBRAPOS:
8833      case OP_ASSERT:
8834      case OP_ONCE:
8835      case OP_ONCE_NC:
8836      d = find_firstassertedchar(scode, &dflags, op == OP_ASSERT);
8837      if (dflags < 0)
8838        return 0;
8839      if (cflags < 0) { c = d; cflags = dflags; } else if (c != d || cflags != dflags) return 0;
8840      break;
8841 
8842      case OP_EXACT:
8843      scode += IMM2_SIZE;
8844      /* Fall through */
8845 
8846      case OP_CHAR:
8847      case OP_PLUS:
8848      case OP_MINPLUS:
8849      case OP_POSPLUS:
8850      if (!inassert) return 0;
8851      if (cflags < 0) { c = scode[1]; cflags = 0; }
8852        else if (c != scode[1]) return 0;
8853      break;
8854 
8855      case OP_EXACTI:
8856      scode += IMM2_SIZE;
8857      /* Fall through */
8858 
8859      case OP_CHARI:
8860      case OP_PLUSI:
8861      case OP_MINPLUSI:
8862      case OP_POSPLUSI:
8863      if (!inassert) return 0;
8864      if (cflags < 0) { c = scode[1]; cflags = REQ_CASELESS; }
8865        else if (c != scode[1]) return 0;
8866      break;
8867      }
8868 
8869    code += GET(code, 1);
8870    }
8871 while (*code == OP_ALT);
8872 
8873 *flags = cflags;
8874 return c;
8875 }
8876 
8877 
8878 
8879 /*************************************************
8880 *     Add an entry to the name/number table      *
8881 *************************************************/
8882 
8883 /* This function is called between compiling passes to add an entry to the
8884 name/number table, maintaining alphabetical order. Checking for permitted
8885 and forbidden duplicates has already been done.
8886 
8887 Arguments:
8888   cd           the compile data block
8889   name         the name to add
8890   length       the length of the name
8891   groupno      the group number
8892 
8893 Returns:       nothing
8894 */
8895 
8896 static void
8897 add_name(compile_data *cd, const pcre_uchar *name, int length,
8898   unsigned int groupno)
8899 {
8900 int i;
8901 pcre_uchar *slot = cd->name_table;
8902 
8903 for (i = 0; i < cd->names_found; i++)
8904   {
8905   int crc = memcmp(name, slot+IMM2_SIZE, IN_UCHARS(length));
8906   if (crc == 0 && slot[IMM2_SIZE+length] != 0)
8907     crc = -1; /* Current name is a substring */
8908 
8909   /* Make space in the table and break the loop for an earlier name. For a
8910   duplicate or later name, carry on. We do this for duplicates so that in the
8911   simple case (when ?(| is not used) they are in order of their numbers. In all
8912   cases they are in the order in which they appear in the pattern. */
8913 
8914   if (crc < 0)
8915     {
8916     memmove(slot + cd->name_entry_size, slot,
8917       IN_UCHARS((cd->names_found - i) * cd->name_entry_size));
8918     break;
8919     }
8920 
8921   /* Continue the loop for a later or duplicate name */
8922 
8923   slot += cd->name_entry_size;
8924   }
8925 
8926 PUT2(slot, 0, groupno);
8927 memcpy(slot + IMM2_SIZE, name, IN_UCHARS(length));
8928 slot[IMM2_SIZE + length] = 0;
8929 cd->names_found++;
8930 }
8931 
8932 
8933 
8934 /*************************************************
8935 *        Compile a Regular Expression            *
8936 *************************************************/
8937 
8938 /* This function takes a string and returns a pointer to a block of store
8939 holding a compiled version of the expression. The original API for this
8940 function had no error code return variable; it is retained for backwards
8941 compatibility. The new function is given a new name.
8942 
8943 Arguments:
8944   pattern       the regular expression
8945   options       various option bits
8946   errorcodeptr  pointer to error code variable (pcre_compile2() only)
8947                   can be NULL if you don't want a code value
8948   errorptr      pointer to pointer to error text
8949   erroroffset   ptr offset in pattern where error was detected
8950   tables        pointer to character tables or NULL
8951 
8952 Returns:        pointer to compiled data block, or NULL on error,
8953                 with errorptr and erroroffset set
8954 */
8955 
8956 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
8957 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8958 pcre_compile(const char *pattern, int options, const char **errorptr,
8959   int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8960 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
8961 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre16 * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8962 pcre16_compile(PCRE_SPTR16 pattern, int options, const char **errorptr,
8963   int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8964 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
8965 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre32 * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8966 pcre32_compile(PCRE_SPTR32 pattern, int options, const char **errorptr,
8967   int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8968 #endif
8969 {
8970 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
8971 return pcre_compile2(pattern, options, NULL, errorptr, erroroffset, tables);
8972 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
8973 return pcre16_compile2(pattern, options, NULL, errorptr, erroroffset, tables);
8974 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
8975 return pcre32_compile2(pattern, options, NULL, errorptr, erroroffset, tables);
8976 #endif
8977 }
8978 
8979 
8980 #if defined COMPILE_PCRE8
8981 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8982 pcre_compile2(const char *pattern, int options, int *errorcodeptr,
8983   const char **errorptr, int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8984 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE16
8985 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre16 * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8986 pcre16_compile2(PCRE_SPTR16 pattern, int options, int *errorcodeptr,
8987   const char **errorptr, int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8988 #elif defined COMPILE_PCRE32
8989 PCRE_EXP_DEFN pcre32 * PCRE_CALL_CONVENTION
8990 pcre32_compile2(PCRE_SPTR32 pattern, int options, int *errorcodeptr,
8991   const char **errorptr, int *erroroffset, const unsigned char *tables)
8992 #endif
8993 {
8994 REAL_PCRE *re;
8995 int length = 1;  /* For final END opcode */
8996 pcre_int32 firstcharflags, reqcharflags;
8997 pcre_uint32 firstchar, reqchar;
8998 pcre_uint32 limit_match = PCRE_UINT32_MAX;
8999 pcre_uint32 limit_recursion = PCRE_UINT32_MAX;
9000 int newline;
9001 int errorcode = 0;
9002 int skipatstart = 0;
9003 BOOL utf;
9004 BOOL never_utf = FALSE;
9005 size_t size;
9006 pcre_uchar *code;
9007 const pcre_uchar *codestart;
9008 const pcre_uchar *ptr;
9009 compile_data compile_block;
9010 compile_data *cd = &compile_block;
9011 
9012 /* This space is used for "compiling" into during the first phase, when we are
9013 computing the amount of memory that is needed. Compiled items are thrown away
9014 as soon as possible, so that a fairly large buffer should be sufficient for
9015 this purpose. The same space is used in the second phase for remembering where
9016 to fill in forward references to subpatterns. That may overflow, in which case
9017 new memory is obtained from malloc(). */
9018 
9019 pcre_uchar cworkspace[COMPILE_WORK_SIZE];
9020 
9021 /* This vector is used for remembering name groups during the pre-compile. In a
9022 similar way to cworkspace, it can be expanded using malloc() if necessary. */
9023 
9024 named_group named_groups[NAMED_GROUP_LIST_SIZE];
9025
